  <h2>Historical Sites and Landmarks in Batangas</h2>

  <div class="gallery">
    <!-- Image 1: Taal Basilica -->
    <div class="image-container">
      <img src="https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-KDs08HNWzcs/YMMu7u_CccI/AAAAAAABOH0/AqzFBP10Zsgln5W4s5CJXAF5dQ4HpRNoACNcBGAsYHQ/s2048/DSC_0429.jpg" alt="Taal Basilica">
      <div class="description">
        The Taal Basilica, located in the town of Taal, is considered the largest Catholic church in Asia. Built in the 16th century, its significance lies in being a witness to various historical events, including the Philippine Revolution against Spanish colonization, where it served as a fortress and refuge for revolutionaries.
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Image 2: Mabini Shrine -->
    <div class="image-container">
      <img src="https://photos.wikimapia.org/p/00/05/79/03/04_big.jpg" alt="Mabini Shrine">
      <div class="description">
        The Mabini Shrine in Tanauan City is the ancestral home of Apolinario Mabini, a key figure in Philippine history known as the "Sublime Paralytic" and the "Brains of the Revolution." This site preserves the legacy of Mabini, who played a pivotal role in drafting the Malolos Constitution during the First Philippine Republic.
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Image 3: Mount Maculot -->
    <div class="image-container">
      <img src="https://media-cdn.tripadvisor.com/media/photo-c/2560x500/05/f9/43/9b/scenic-view-from-maculot.jpg" alt="Mount Maculot">
      <div class="description">
        Mount Maculot, located in Cuenca, is not only a scenic hiking destination but also has historical significance. During World War II, it served as a guerrilla base against Japanese forces, showcasing the resilience and resistance of the Filipino people in the face of occupation.
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Image 4: Casa Villavicencio -->
    <div class="image-container">
      <img src="https://mb.com.ph/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/IMG_2540-1024x563.jpg">
      <div class="description">
        Casa Villavicencio in Taal is an ancestral house that played a pivotal role during the Philippine Revolution against Spanish rule. It served as a meeting place for revolutionaries, including key figures like Jose Rizal, making it an essential site in the struggle for Philippine independence.
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Image 5: Casa de Segunda -->
    <div class="image-container">
      <img src="https://outoftownblog.com/casa-de-segunda-a-national-heritage-house-in-lipa/casa-de-segunda-photo-by-renz-marion-katigbak/" alt="Mount Maculot">
      <div class="description">
        Also known as the Luz-Katigbak Ancestral House in Lipa City, is a well-preserved heritage house with historical significance. It was the residence of Segunda Katigbak, a noted figure in Philippine history and known as the "First Lady of the Revolution." As the alleged first love of national hero Jose Rizal, this house stands as a symbol of the intertwining of personal relationships and historical events during the Philippine Revolution against Spanish rule.
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Image 6: San Jose Church (Saint Joseph the Patriarch Parish)
 -->
    <div class="image-container">
      <img src="https://wowbatangas.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/St.-Joseph-the-Patriarch-Parish-Church-19.jpg" alt="San Jose Church (Saint Joseph the Patriarch Parish)">
      <div class="description">
        San Jose Church in Batangas City is a centuries-old church that has withstood the tests of time, serving as a testament to the enduring influence of Spanish colonial architecture. The church played a role in the propagation of Christianity during the Spanish era, marking an important chapter in the Philippines' religious history.

      </div>
    </div>

